The study of other species' communication systems may give insight into the development and function of language in humans. Bee and parrot communication systems, for example, have been thoroughly examined and shown to have some parallels with human language. The use of symbols or signals to express certain thoughts or things is something that bees and parrots have in common with human language. Bees, for example, utilize a "waggle dance" to transmit the location of food to the rest of the colony. The dance's direction and length serve as a signal or indicator for the location of the meal. Similarly, unique cries have been discovered in parrots to express the presence of predators or the need for food. Another feature shared by bees and parrots is the capacity to combine symbols or signals to communicate more complicated information. Bees, for example, may communicate the distance and direction of food sources by integrating information from the waggle dance with the odor of the food. Similarly, diverse combinations of cries have been seen in parrots to transmit different forms of information, such as the presence of predators or the need for food. Human language, on the other hand, is distinct in numerous respects. One of the most significant distinctions is the capacity to produce an unlimited number of sentences by combining a finite amount of words. This is referred to as "productivity" in human language. This is unique to human language; no other species has been shown to be capable of creating new meaning by mixing symbols or signals in this manner. Furthermore, human language is exceptional in its capacity to transmit abstract and metaphorical notions such as emotions, beliefs, and ideas. The use of grammar and syntax is another feature of human language that distinguishes it from other animal communication systems. Human language is governed by a sophisticated system of laws that control the order and arrangement of words and sentences, allowing us to transmit nuanced meaning and information in an organized manner. Other animal communication methods do not have this feature. Finally, investigating other creatures' communication systems may give insight into the development and function of language in humans. While some aspects of human language are shared with other animals, such as the use of symbols or signs and the ability to combine symbols or signs to convey more complex messages, human language is unique in its productivity, ability to convey abstract and metaphorical concepts, and use of grammar and syntax. 